seg.hi: A note on the display of images:

summary.seg:
In several places in the manuscript, a single sheet document has been folded in two and placed around the outside of a quire. Some may have functioned as protective wrappers while those quires circulated separately, prior to their binding between covers with the rest of the manuscript. When bound into the manuscript, one half of such a document appears before the first leaf of the quire, and the other after the last leaf of the quire. When the manuscript came into the possession of Matthew Parker, the leaves were paginated in the characteristic red/orange crayon, with only odd numbers appearing on the recto side of each leaf. Since each half of these documents formed a leaf in the manuscript, these too were paginated in the same sequence, as follows:
pp. 1-2 + 3-4 [not enclosing other leaves]
pp. 39-40 + 41-42 [not enclosing other leaves]
pp. 77-78 + 79-80 [not enclosing other leaves]
pp. 235-236 + 257-258 [enclosing pp. 237-256]
pp. 243-244 + 249-250 [enclosing pp. 245-248]
pp. 299-300 + 311-312 [encloding pp. 301-310]
pp. 313-314 + 323-324 [enclosing pp. 315-322]

When the manuscript was rebound in 1952, all but the last of these folded sheets was released, in order that the text they bore could be read. The fourth, fifth and six of those listed above were placed before the beginning of the quire they had previously enclosed. For reasons that are not clear, the seventh was never released, but remained bound in around pp. 315-322. The manuscript was disbound between 2005 and 2009, in preparation for its digitisation, and these bifolia were photographed as separate leaves and fully opened so that their text could be read across a single image. Once again, the seventh folded document was not given this treatment, and was photographed only as two separate leaves. As of 2012, the manuscript has been rebound in a limp parchment binding, matching the 1953 rearrangement but also releasing the seventh folded document and placing it before the leaves it formerly enclosed. This binding and its accompanying endleaves are recorded in this description but have not been digitised.

The display of the images on the Parker Library on the Web is intended to show the manuscript's leaves in their sequence prior to the 1953 rearrangement and rebinding, but also to show the full text of these folded sheets once they have been opened up. The sequence the images follow is: the recto and then the verso of the first half of the folded sheet is shown, followed by the full opening, the rectos and versos of the enclosed leaves, and finally the recto and verso of the second half of the folded sheet. The presentation of pp. 39-40 + 41-42 is more complicated, because the sheet was folded in such a way that its text ran around the back of the sheet (not around the inside), and because the beginning of the text falls on the last page (p. 42) and its end on the first page (p. 39). As explained above, the one exception is the seventh sheet, which was not photographed fully opened across pp. 314 and 323.

For the Cambridge Digital Library, it has been decided instead to show the images in the sequence that they now appear in the manuscript. The sequence the images follow is: the recto and then the verso of the first half of the folded sheet is shown, followed by the full opening, the recto and then the verso of the second half of the folded sheet, and then the rectos and versos of the leaves they enclosed. The pagination still follows that written in red/orange crayon, and where an opening is shown both page numbers are given: for example, pp. 42-39, or pp. 78-79. The textual contents of these folded leaves will be described only where the sheet is shown fully opened. Since the seventh folded sheet has been released, images of pp. 314 and 323 are adjacent to one another, and occur before the images of the leaves they formerly enclosed (pp. 315-322).

Dr James Freeman
Medieval Manuscripts Specialist
Cambridge University Library

supportDesc.support: Paper leaves with inserted legal documents and letters on single paper sheets.

note.p: NB: These dimensions correspond to the range of leaves found in the manuscript's core part (Part 2) to give a sense of the manuscript's tall and narrow shape. The dimensions of the other parts are ignored here because they concern inserted leaves that typically have been bound in vertically and their original height and width have been cropped to match the dimensions of the manuscript's core part.

As Rundle (2024) points out, the format of this mansucript is that of a so-called 'holster book'. Two other extant notebooks from Worcestre (London, British Library, Cotton MS Julius F VII and London, British Library, Sloane MS 4) and his account book (London, British Library, Add MS 28208) are in the same format.

foliation.p: 16th-century Parkerian pagination, with supplementary numbering for fragmentary leaves supplied by a modern hand:
Numbering (odd numbers only) in red crayon in the upper right-hand corners of the rectos, by Matthew Parker (1504-1575) Parker, Matthew, 1504-1575.

The leaves that contain pages 30a-30b, 294a-294b, and 304a-304b are fragmentary and have been restored to their original sizes with blank paper in modern times. The leaf that contains pages 330a-330b is a stub with a few scribles or notes written on it. The leaves were not paginated by Matthew Parker: a modern hand has written numbers with 'a' and 'b' supplements in pencil in the upper outer corners of both sides of these leaves. There is also one fragmentary leaf restored with blank paper that may have been paginated by Parker. This concerns the manuscript's final leaf to which a modern hand has added the numbers '333' and '334' in pencil to the upper outer corners of both sides of the leaf.

The square brackets that contain two numbers (i.e. [2-3], [42-39], [78-79], [236-257], [244-249], [300-311]) refer to images that show texts that run across two pages. These typically involve pre-existing documents that Worcestre inserted into this manuscript, except for pp. [78 and 79] which contains a text by Worcestre that is part of the Itineraria and runs across two pages. These numbers have been added to the foliation statement for reference purposes in this eletronic catalogue record.

Folios [i]-[iv] and [v]-[viii] are unfoliated/unpaginated modern paper flyleaves at the beginning and end of the manuscript [not photographed] that have been allocated Roman numerals for reference purposes in this catalogue record. These numbers have been placed between square brackets to indicate that they have been supplied.

When the manuscript was rebound in 1953, it was decided to re-organise inserted leaves that originally were folded around the outsides of quires, and this new organisation was maintained when the manuscript was given its current binding in 2012. Consequently, Parker's pagination sequence is out of order. For a reconstruction of the manuscript's original order, see Harvey (1969), pp. 407-416 ('Conspectus of Pages').

collation.formula: The collation of the manuscript's current structure - which does not reflect its original division into quires - has not been established, but it contains many short booklets of 2 and 4 leaves. It also features inserted single documents that have been folded into bifolia and to which William Worcestre has added notes from his Itineraria. Because these documents were produced separately from this manuscript, they are treated as separate parts in this catalogue record.

binding.p: The manuscript has a limp parchment binding [not photographed] that dates to 2012. It consists of veiny parchment that has been folded over thin paper covers laced onto an alum-tawed goatskin spine-covering featuring green headbands with six thongs of alum-tawed skin.

The current binding (2012) replaces a binding that was made by the bookbinder John P. Gray of Cambridge in 1952. The latter has been preserved but is kept separately from the manuscript [not photographed]. It concerns a binding of brown leather over wooden boards with blind-tooled vertical 'teeth' on the covers that correspond with the positions of five raised bands on the spine. The latter features the gold-stamped classmark: MS. 210 and C.C.C.C.. The old binding is accompanied by two old paper flyleaves at the beginning, numerous rigid paper stubs, and two old paper flyleaves at the end. The classmark MS 210 is inscribed in ink on the first flyleaf at the beginning with a note about Gray.

When the manuscript was re-bound in 1952, single documents that William Worcestre had folded around the outsides of quires were relocated so that they could be read across the fold without interuption. This modern organisation was maintained when the manuscript was bound again in 2012.

provenance.p: William Worcestre [Worcester] [Botoner] (1415–1480x85) Worcestre [Worcester] [Botoner], William, 1415–1480x85, secretary to Sir John Fastolf (1380-1459), antiquary, topographer, and chronicler: copied and owned the manuscript. A colophon in his own hand on p. 5: Willelmus worcetor [sic] est author huius libri .vi. post .fo. 4.. His name inscribed on p. 106 (lower margin): Botiner qui est Wurcester. His name inscribed on p. 118: Nomen patris [...] qui hunc librum scripsit W. Wurcester. Four other manuscripts with Worcestre's hand survive, including an account book concerning his surveyorship of the Manor of Castle combe, Wiltshire, for John Fastolf (London, British Library, Add MS 28208); his commonplace book (London, British Library, Cotton MS Julius F VII); a compilation of historical texts copied by different hands, including Worcestre's (London, British Library, Royal MS 13 C I) and a medical manuscript (London, British Library, Sloane MS 4). Worcestre's hand also occurs in Geoffrey Chaucer's Middle English translation of Boethius's De consolatione philosophiae in Cambridge, Pembroke College, MS 215. As Daniel Wakelin points out (see his Introduction to Pembroke College, MS 215), Worcestre appears to have used Chaucer's translation to read the original Latin passages from Boethius (book IV, metre 3 and prose 3) that he copied on p. 194 of Corpus Christi College MS 210. This is suggested by the fact that he has highlighted the same passage in the Middle English version on ff. 66r-66v of Cambridge, Pembroke College, MS 215.
T.M. la Rosarius (fl. 16th century) Rosarius, T.M. la, 16th century: owned or accessed the manuscript. Their name inscribed on p. 219: T.M. LA. ROSARIVS . brugensis - I.R. Rosarius la - I.R..

Robert Talbot (c. 1505-1558) Talbot, Robert c. 1505-1558, prebendary of Norwich Cathedral (from 1547) and treasurer there until his death: copied information from the Registrum Primum of Norwich Cathedral on p. 226.

Francis Rugge (1536-1607) Rugge, Francis, 1536-1607, Freeman of Norwich in 1563, alderman from c. 1570 onwards, Sheriff of Norwich in 1572-3, and Mayor of Norwich in 1587-9: his name (ffrauncis Rugge) inscribed on p. 286. While Harvey suggests that his name is written in the hand of that of Henry Aldrich (whose name occurs twice on the same page together with scribles), it is also possible that it was added by Rugge himself, either as an owner or user of the manuscript. Although Harvey does not identify Thomas Rugge, he almost certainly is the freeman, alderman, sheriff, and mayor of Norwhich who married Anne Aldrich (d. 1611). The latter was a daughter of John Aldrich (1520-1582), alderman and mercer of Norwich, and mayor of that city in 1570-71, and Elizabeth, daughter of Nicholas Sotherton (d.1540), alderman and Mayor of Norwich (1539-40), and sister of Henry Aldrich [see below] whose name is twice inscribed above that of Francis Rugge on p. 286.

Henry Aldrich (d. 1593) Aldrich, Henry, d. 1593, Fellow of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge, in 1569-1579; who was licensed to teach grammar in Norwich in 1583: his name inscribed on p. 286: Henricus Aldrichius and Henry Aldryche. His name inscriptions are accompanied by many pen trials, including initials and names (Mr Master Bristlye) that appear to have been written by the same hand. Henry may have inscribed the name of Thomas Rugge [probably his brother-in-law; see above] and a list of first names: Thomas / Henry / John / Michael / Thomas / John / Henry [This list may refer to the sons of John Aldrich and Elizabeth Sotherton: aside from a son named Henry, there were sons named John, Michael, and Thomas]. The name of Christian Aldrich (Christian Aldrichus) - who remains unidentified but almost certainly was a relative of Henry - is inscribed (upside down) in light brown ink on p. 278. According to Harvey (1969), the manuscript probably passed from Aldrich to Corpus Christi College but the presence of pagination in the hand of Matthew Parker (see below) and the existence of a partial transcription in a manuscript (now Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 101) that was copied for Matther Parker from books in his collection and elsewhere suggest otherwise. Venn ALDC563H

Matthew Parker (1504-1575) Parker, Matthew, 1504-1575, archbishop of Canterbury: not recorded in his register of books donated Corpus Christi College, now Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 575, but his ownership is suggested by the presence of his pagination in red crayon throughout. As Rand (2009) notes, Parker owned two other notebooks that belonged to Robert Talbot. These are now Cambridge, Corpus Christi MS 111 and Cambridge, Corpus Christi MS 379.

acquisition.p: The College's classmark CCCC MS 210 has been inscribed in pencil on f [i] recto of current binding [not photographed]. Listed as item no. 377 (Gu. Worcester de ciuitatibus, monasterijs et Abbatijs, deque longitudine et latitudine earum, rebusque memorabilibus) in Thomas James's Ecloga Oxonio-Catabrigiensis, printed in London in 1600. Item 378 in Edward Bernard and Humfrey Wanley, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ, in unum collecti, cum indice alphabetico printed in Oxford in 1697. Item 13 in Libri ab alienis donati (Miscellanea quaedam Gulielmi de Worcester, lectu difficilia, et parvi, uti credo, momenti) in William Stanley, Catalogus librorum manuscriptorum in Bibliotheca Collegiis Corporis Christi in Cantabrigia: Quos legauit Matthaeus Parkerus Archiepiscopus Cantuariensis, printed in London in 1722 (see also the inscription B.5 on f. ii recto). Item 210 in James Nasmith, Catalogus librorum manuscriptorum quos Collegio Corporis Christi et B. Mariae Virginis in Academia Cantabrigiensis legauit Reverendissimus in Christo Pater Matthaeus Parker, Archiepiscopus Cantuariensis (Cambridge, 1777).

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on M.R. James, A Descriptive Catalogue of the Manuscripts in the Library of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge, 2 vols (Cambridge, 1912), no. 210; and Kari Anne Rand, Manuscripts in the Library of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge, The Index of Middle English Prose, Handlist XX (Cambridge: Brewer, 2009), pp. 28-33. Images and a description of the manuscript are also available on the Parker Library website: the online catalogue entry for the item published at Parker on the Web Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 210.

msItem.title: Itineraria [Itineraries]
msItem.author: William Worcestre [Worcester] [Botoner]
msItem.incipit: 5 longitudo Ecclesie sancte marie Tynterne continet 77 \uel 75/ virgas
msItem.explicit: 332 Ve michi nascente ; ve nato ; ve morienti / Ve michi ; quod sine ue non viuit filius Eue

note.p: NB: William Worcestre has inserted six documents into this manuscript that were created as separate textual units by other scribes and has added texts that are part of the Itineraria to them. This catalogue record treats these documents as separate parts. Parts 1, 3, 4, 5, 6, and 7 should be consulted for further items of the Itineraria.
This catalogue record follows the edition of Harvey (1969) and considers a few items in Worcestre's hand as separate from the Itineraria.
Page 333 is a torn leaf with a fragmentary text that has not been read (no text is visible on the reverse of this leaf or p. 334).

Aside from historical and topographical information, the Itineraria include a wide range of other materials that evidently were of interest to Worcestre. For example, it includes a multiplication table that is attributed to Thomas Hengham, monk of Norwich Priory (Multiplicacio numerorum secundum laborem dompni Thome Hengham religiosi monasterij Norwicensis), on p. 261 [perhaps Thomas Ingham, monk scholar of Norwich, who was at Cambridge in 1466-67; see Harvey (1969), p. 239 fn. 1]; a list of Arabic terms for parts of the Astrolabe (Termeni arabici in jnstrumento astrolabij) on p. 261]; and notes on the art of grammar (Priscianus in Maiori) on p. 320.

msItem.title: Medical recipe for gall or bladder stone
msItem.textLang: Latin recipe with Middle English title
msItem.incipit: 12 Ad sanandum lapidem . recipe herba vocat Anglice perspeere . que crescit prope terram in patria Catiswold et super mures castri Dover
msItem.explicit: 12 et bibe de isto puluere nocte et mane cum seruisia desicata et sanabitur infra breue hec est practica Roberti Wardale
msItem.note: Copied by William Worcestre. The Robert Wardale who Worcestre associates with this recipe has not been identified before but is likely to be the Robert Wardale who served under John Fastolf and was at the siege of Pontorson in 1427 (on him, see Thomas Christian Bernard Drewitt-Wex, 'The English 'Soldier' c.1400-1461: Perceptions of Professionalism and Criminality' (unpublished doctoral thesis, University of Winchester, 2019), pp. 90 and 254.

supportDesc.support: Paper, folded in folio. Pages 5-30, 30a-30b, 31-38, 43-188, 188a-188b, 189-234, 237-242, 245-248, 251-256, 259-294, 294a-294b, 295-298, 301-304, 304a-304b, 305-310, 315-322, 325-330, 330a-330b, 331-334: various watermarks, including: Letter P, unicorn, bull's head with five-pointed star, anchor, coat of arms with cross.

collation.note: The collation for Part 2 (the core of the manuscript) has not been established.

signatures.p: Roman numerals (ii to xvij) written in dark ink on the lower outer corners of the first rectos of pages 5, 9, 13, 17, 21, 25, 27, 31, 35, 47, 51, 55, 59, 61, 67, and 69.

p.seg: Hardpoint ruling (vertical line in the inside margin only). Single columns. c. 40-c. 50 lines to the page.

handNote.p: Copied by William Worcestre [Worcester] [Botoner] (1415–1480x85) Worcestre [Worcester] [Botoner], William, 1415–1480x85 in a cursive hand with anglicana features.

decoNote.p: On p. 129 is a drawing in plummet of the outline (jamb mould) of the stonework on the South porch of St Stephen's Church, Bristol, attributed to the freemason Benedict Cross. Inside the outline is written: Thys ys the Jamemoold of the porthe dore yn the southsyde of the chyrch of seynt stevyn (see Harvey (1969), pp. 316-317).
On p. 84, drawings of three coats of arms in brown ink, without colours but two have blazons written inside their escutcheons (see Harvey (1969), pp. 342-343).

On p. 223 are two nativity charts (horoscopes) for 3 September 1480, one for 6pm (Figure celi die .3. mensis Septembris hora .6. post meridiem anno .1480. de elongacione [?] secundum [?] etcaetera) and another for 5pm (Figura anno mense et die supradictis hora circa .5.ta de elongacione [?] secundum etcaetera). [see Harvey (1969), pp. 300-301].

note.p: Added to Worcestre's Itineraria are many annotations by later hands. For example, on p. 74 a later (?) 15th- or 16th-century hand as has added: In ye Cittye of great Troye was a noble knyght / he meaneth Brutus as ys expressid in other place of thys booke; on p. 95 (lower margin). Many of the annotations are in the hand of Robert Talbot. For example, he repeated Worcestre's comment on the grammarian John Leland the Elder (d. 1428): Vt Rosa flos florum sic leland grammaticorum (p. 95); supplied titles for Worcestre's journeys, e.g. Itinerarium a Norwico ad montem S. Michaelis (p. 60); titles for subjects. e.g. Oratio pro itinerantibus and S. Brandan Worcestre's prayers to the Three Magi and St Brendan for safe travels (p. 106); and Catalogus operum Domini Johannis grossthead episcopi Lincoln for Worcestre's list of the works of Robert Grosseteste (p. 193).

msItem.title: Letter of R. Botoner to William Worcestre
msItem.explicit: 42 Sir youre blissyng and my modirs desirid I sent yow a letter by Master Paston man. Which is in that contre etcaetera. Sir I am with my maister Lovel God geue me grace to plese hym. And sir he wol nedis haue a bed and I haue take youre bed except feither-bed and bolster etcaetera. Sir your hostes made suche wark that I am not fare with her they wold nat let me haue the bed tyll my coson sent his man

39 No more etcaetera but God prospere you I pray yow comaund me to my modir and sister and brodir and all my frendis I pray yow remembre my mater I here no word of the ansuere of W.B. deuandes etcaetera youre boke is to Wynchestre etcaetera. Wrete on Tuesday iijd weke of Lent - R. Botoner
msItem.finalRubric: 41 To William Worcestre this be delyuered / In hast etcaetera / loth to offend
msItem.note: Dallaway (1834) identifies the writer as Worcestre's son Richard. The letter, which mentions Thomas Kent and a letter from a male member of the Paston family, is undated but may have been written between c 1460-c. 1480. Afther the death of John Fastolf in 1459, Worcestre, Fastolf's former secretary, became much involved with John Paston, one of Fastolf's executors, concerning the distribution of his possessions.
Written across p. 39 are the numbers 1448 [deleted: 1449]; and 1330 [deleted: 1330] in different ink.

msItem.title: On the River Severn and River Dee, Wales [= Part of William Worcestre's Itineraria]
msItem.rubric: 300 The Jnformacion of Sir Roger Kenerston of Shropshyre
msItem.incipit: 300 Sevarn - The hede of the water of Sevarn begynneth in a hye hill called Plimlvmon and from the seid hille hit renneth down to Lanydlos and from thens to Kaersyoys
msItem.explicit: 311 and from thens to Eyton is boote . and from thens to Chestre and so fourth to the sey

note.p: Sir Roger Kynaston (b. c. 1433-1495) was High Sheriff of Shropshire in both 1461 and 1470 and knighted after the Battle of Tewkesbury in 1471, which may provide an indication of when this document was written.
The text has been annotated by Robert Talbot.
